                  </persName>
            . I am an headborough. I saw the prisoner roll this puncheon across Tabernacle-walk. The prisoner said he did not take the puncheon; I told him, he might clear himself at the office. At the office he said he bought it of another man.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was passing along Old-street, a person asked me if I would roll a puncheon as far as the Curtain-road, he would pay me. A person followed me, and said he believed it was his puncheon; I said, I believe not; the person that belongs to it is behind me, and when I looked round, the man was gone.</p>
